Appendix D: Extended Scenario Analysis & Stress Test Protocol

D.1 Formal Scenario Definitions

Scenario Governing Principle Key Parameter Shifts Expected Macro Signature
Green Discontinuity Preemptive Coupling: SGI development is coupled with and prioritized for physical system optimization. - High f_alloc_E, f_alloc_T (≥0.3 each) - High η_E, η_T - Policy-driven g_{S_clean} > 7% - Rising ρ_power over time 1. Short-term (1-10 yrs): High investment, moderate growth. 2. Medium-term (10-30 yrs): C_phys peaks and declines. σ_effective uncouples from σ_raw, leading to accelerating, sustainable growth.
Constrained Discontinuity Cognitive Decoupling: SGI capability races ahead of physical infrastructure. - Low f_alloc to physical sectors (<0.1 each) - ρ_power stagnant - g_{S_clean} follows business-as-usual (~3%) 1. Short-term: Rapid initial GDP bumps from software/service automation. 2. Medium-term: C_phys rises sharply. σ_effective plateaus. 3. Long-term: Growth stalls, high inflation in hardware/energy, high probability of a major financial shock (S_t).
Managed Transition Adaptive Governance: Policy reacts to emerging bottlenecks. - f_alloc parameters adjust dynamically in response to rising C_phys. - Moderate initial investment in physical tech. An "S-curve" trajectory: initial lag, followed by accelerated growth as policies kick in, aiming to asymptotically approach the Green Discontinuity path.

D.2 Stress Test Protocol: Compute Energy Density (ρ_power)

Objective: To identify the threshold at which stagnation in compute energy density causes systemic collapse, and to quantify the intervention required to prevent it.

Procedure:

1. Baseline Run: Set g_{ρ_power} = 0% (no improvement in W/m²). Run the Constrained Discontinuity scenario.
2. Identify Collapse Metrics:
   · Record the year t_collapse when σ_effective peaks and begins a sustained decline despite rising σ_raw.
   · Record the maximum achieved C_phys and the corresponding GDP loss relative to a scenario with unconstrained σ_raw.
3. Intervention Sweep: For a range of target ρ_power growth rates (e.g., 0%, 2%, 5%, 10% p.a.):
   · Set the required f_alloc_T and η_T to achieve that growth rate.
   · Run the model and record the long-term (e.g., Year 50) GDP, σ_effective, and C_phys.
4. Analysis: Plot the results. The curve will show a sharp nonlinear transition—a "phase change"—from a collapsed to a thriving regime at a critical minimum ρ_power growth rate. This critical point defines a minimum viable investment in cooling/physical compute R&D.

Interpretation: This stress test provides a quantifiable engineering target for policymakers and industry: "To avoid a civilizational growth stall, aggregate R&D must sustain at least an X% annual improvement in computational energy density."
